PM components could perturb mitochondrial function, leading to generation of ROS and cell death [21,60]. Mitochondria have been shown to be a direct subcellular target for ambient UFPs. For example, ambient UFPs have been found to lodge in the mitochondria of target cells and cause mitochondrial damage [21]. Although the mechanism of mitochondrial localization is still elusive, we hypothesize that particle size, hydrophobicity and presence of organic chemicals may play a role in the process. In addition to direct effects, studies have found that organic PM chemicals are capable of generating ROS by their ability to interfere in these electron transfer events. This includes the effect of polar chemicals such as redox-cycling quinones to disrupt electron transfer in the inner membrane [44]. This disruption in electron flow could favor the formation of ubisemiquinones, thereby contributing to mitochondrial O2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
